  "response": "NSS can refer to several different things, depending on the context. Here are the most common meanings:\n\n*   **National Security Strategy (NSS):** This is a document produced periodically by the executive branch of the U.S. government that outlines the country's strategic goals and priorities related to national security. It is a key policy document that guides the actions of various government agencies and departments.\n\n*   **Network Security Services (NSS):** This is a set of open-source libraries designed to support cross-platform development of security-enabled client and server applications. It was originally developed by Netscape and is now maintained by Mozilla. NSS provides cryptographic functions, security protocols (like TLS/SSL), and other security-related tools.\n\nTo give you a more precise answer, please provide more context. For example:\n\n*   \"I saw an article about the NSS of the United States...\" (likely refers to the National Security Strategy)\n*   \"I'm trying to encrypt my email using NSS...\" (likely refers to Network Security Services)",
